==Treatment==

[[Smoking cessation]] and [[exercise]] therapy (regular walking) are useful both for treatment of arterial insufficiency and its [[prophylaxis]]. Two medications currently are approved by the U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) for treatment of intermittent claudication: [[pentoxifylline]] (hemorheologic agent) and [[cilostazol]] (phosphodiesterase inhibitor).

===Surgery===

The type of operation depends on the anatomic level and extent of arterial disease:
*[[Aortofemoral]] or extra-anatomic bypass for ''aortoiliac disease''
*Infrainguinal bypass for ''[[femoral artery|femoral]]'', ''[[popliteal artery|popliteal]]'', ''[[Posterior tibial artery|tibial]]'' disease

===Diet===

While there is no direct association between arterial insufficiency and [[diet (nutrition)|diet]], a [[low fat]], [[cholesterol|low cholesterol]] [[diet (nutrition)|diet]] is generally recommended.

===Activity===
Regular [[Walking|walking exercise]] at least 30 minutes 3 times a week is recommended.

